        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Live Roller Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Live Roller Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Live Roller Conveyor Systems
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A live roller conveyor is any roller conveyor where the rollers are actively driven by a power source, as opposed to <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/gravity/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">gravity roller conveyors</a> where rollers spin freely. The three conventional live roller drive technologies are belt-driven live roller (BDLR), line-shaft, and chain-driven live roller (CDLR). <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR (Motor Driven Roller)</a> represents a fourth, newer approach where the motor sits inside the roller itself. This page compares all four technologies head-to-head to help you select the right live roller system for your application.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Technology Overview -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="tech-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technology Overview</div>
      <h2 id="tech-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Four Live Roller <span class="text-accent">Drive Technologies</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt-Driven Live Roller (BDLR)</h3>
        <p>BDLR conveyors use a continuous flat belt running beneath the rollers. The belt contacts the underside of each roller through friction. A single AC gearmotor at one end drives the belt via a drive pulley. Tension is maintained by a spring-loaded take-up. BDLR handles the widest load range of the three conventional live roller types , up to 500 lbs per product at speeds of 50-200 FPM.</p>
        <p>BDLR provides the foundation for most <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">powered roller conveyor</a> installations. Hytrol, Dematic, and Intelligrated offer extensive BDLR product lines. With added pneumatic zone controls (belt lifters or pop-up stops), BDLR supports both zero-pressure and minimum-pressure <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Line-Shaft</h3>
        <p>A line-shaft conveyor uses a continuously rotating splined steel shaft running the conveyor length. Individual polyurethane O-ring bands connect each roller to the shaft. The shaft rotates via an AC gearmotor, and O-rings transfer rotation from shaft to roller. Line-shaft conveyors handle up to 300 lbs at 30-180 FPM.</p>
        <p>The O-ring connection provides a built-in slip clutch , if a product stops, the O-ring slips on the shaft rather than stalling the motor. This passive slip provides a degree of light <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a> without active zone control. Line-shaft works particularly well with pop-up <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer</a> sections because the O-ring can be disengaged from stopped rollers in the transfer zone without affecting adjacent rollers.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Chain-Driven Live Roller (CDLR)</h3>
        <p><a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR conveyors</a> use roller chains and sprockets to positively drive all rollers. The chain-and-sprocket engagement provides zero-slip positive drive at any load. CDLR handles 500 to over 10,000 lbs per product at 20-120 FPM. CDLR serves as the standard live roller technology for <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pallet conveyor systems</a> and heavy industrial applications.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Motor Driven Roller (MDR)</h3>
        <p><a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> place a 24VDC brushless DC motor inside the roller tube itself. Each motor roller drives 2-4 adjacent slave rollers via O-ring bands, creating an independent zone. MDR handles up to 250 lbs per zone at 20-180 FPM. MDR provides built-in zero-pressure accumulation without pneumatics, belts, or chains, and has become the dominant technology for new conveyor installations in distribution and fulfillment.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

