  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Live Roller <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">End-of-line packaging:</strong> BDLR and MDR transport sealed cases between case sealers, labelers, and palletizers. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation zones</a> buffer cases before the palletizer. CDLR handles loaded pallets between the palletizer and stretch wrapper.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Distribution and fulfillment:</strong> MDR dominates new distribution center installations for tote and carton transport with ZPA. Line-shaft conveyors remain common in legacy systems and diverter-intensive layouts.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Food and beverage:</a></strong> Stainless steel BDLR and MDR conveyors handle cased goods in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary</a> and washdown environments. Open-frame construction and sealed bearings support cleaning protocols.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Pallet handling:</strong> <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR</a> is the only live roller technology rated for full pallet loads. <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Pallet conveyor systems</a> use CDLR for transport, right-angle chain <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfers</a> for routing, and <a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">VRCs</a> for vertical transport.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Assembly and manufacturing:</strong> Live roller conveyors transport work-in-process between assembly stations. <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Indexing configurations</a> stop and start products at each station for manual or robotic operations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a live roller conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>Any <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyor</a> where rollers are actively powered. The four technologies are BDLR (belt-driven), line-shaft, <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">CDLR</a> (chain-driven), and <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a> (motor inside roller).</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            BDLR vs line-shaft , what is the difference?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>BDLR uses a belt under rollers (friction drive, up to 500 lbs). Line-shaft uses a splined shaft with O-rings (up to 300 lbs, natural slip-clutch). BDLR handles heavier loads. Line-shaft suits diverting and light accumulation. See <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">powered roller conveyors</a> for details.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Should I choose MDR or belt-driven live roller?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
            <p>MDR for zone control, ZPA, energy efficiency, and low noise (under 250 lbs). BDLR for heavier loads (250-500 lbs), continuous transport, or lower upfront budget. MDR delivers lower total cost of ownership over 15-20 years.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
